  "chunk_index": 37,
  "summary": "Hercule Poirot reveals that Franklin Clarke is the true \"ABC\" killer. Poirot explains that Clarke intentionally misdelivered the third letter to him by using a clever address error—\"White Harbor - White Horse\"—to ensure a private detective would receive it rather than the police, allowing Clarke to escape the crime scene before an investigation could begin. While Clarke's ultimate motive was to kill his brother, he staged a third murder at Tancaster to prevent suspicion regarding the abrupt end of the alphabetical pattern.\n\nTo frame Alexander Bonaparte Cast, Clarke staged a crime at a cinema by stabbing a random man in the dark, placing the ABC book on the victim, and then bumping into Cast. Clarke wiped the knife on Cast's sleeve and planted it in his pocket. Due to Cast's epilepsy and subsequent memory gaps, Cast believed he had committed the murders himself. Poirot clarifies that he knew Cast was innocent and that Clarke had used a weighted club for the Andover and Cheltenham murders. Evidence against Clarke included witness identifications in Bexhill and, most decisively, Clarke's fingerprints on Cast's typewriter.\n\nWhen confronted, Clarke attempts suicide with a revolver, but Poirot's valet had previously pickpocketed the gun and removed the bullets. Clarke is subsequently arrested by Scotland Yard detectives. In the aftermath, Poirot explains his methods to Hastings, admitting that the fingerprint evidence was a bluff intended to break Clarke's composure. Later, Cast visits the group—now a celebrity due to the case—and expresses his intent to sell his story to the newspapers.",
